    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a good start. Can you add a section that explains why this concept is considered so essential for modern democracy? Like, why would a country be 'less free' if they only had procedural due process without the substantive side of things?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Procedural due process only ensures the *fairness* of the process—like getting a trial—but substantive due process protects the actual *rights* within that process. Without it, a government could theoretically follow all the correct procedures to strip away fundamental liberties, such as making arbitrary laws restricting personal freedom. Substantive due process acts as a necessary bulwark, ensuring that the government cannot use its procedural power to enact fundamentally unjust laws or violate core human dignity. This combination is vital for a democracy because procedural fairness is hollow without substantive rights to protect.",
      "source": "target",
